HOUSE CONCURRENT RESOLUTION NO. 114
BY REPRESENTATIVE DEWITT
HEALTH: Directs the Louisiana Board of Medical Examiners to study the feasibility and
practicality of creating a physician review panel
1 A CONCURRENT RESOLUTION
2 To authorize and direct the Louisiana State Board of Medical Examiners to study the
3 feasibility and advisability of establishing a physician review panel process for
4 certain complaints against physicians prior to escalation to formal disciplinary
5 proceedings, with respect to the scope of the study, for consultation with interested
6 parties, for a report of findings and recommendations, and to provide for related
7 matters.
8 WHEREAS, House Bill No. 1227 of the 2026 Regular Session proposed the creation
9 of a physician peer review panel process for complaints involving clinical decision making,
10 diagnosis, treatment, prescribing, supervision of clinical care, documentation of care, and
11 standard of care; and
12 WHEREAS, complaints involving medical judgment may present issues distinct
13 from complaints primarily involving billing disputes, fee disputes, other financial
14 complaints, or allegations of sexual misconduct; and
15 WHEREAS, creating a physician review panel process should be carefully studied
16 with respect to physician qualifications, board certification requirements, specialty matching,
17 selection procedures, timing, confidentiality protections, compensation, costs, and the
18 interaction of such a process with existing investigative deadlines and disciplinary authority
19 of the Louisiana State Board of Medical Examiners (LSBME); and
20 WHEREAS, a study is necessary over a two-year period before determining whether
21 to enact a statutory physician review panel process.
